text:
The Concordia Parish School Board will interview five candidates for superintendent this week.  Interviews are scheduled for 5:30 p.m. on both Wednesday and Thursday at the school board office, located at 4358 U.S. 84 in Vidalia.

Board President Fred Butcher confirmed that five of the original eight applicants remain.  Three candidates—Troy Bell of Winnsboro, James Stoder of Rogersville, Tennessee, and Chanel Howard-Veazy of Crockett, Texas—withdrew their applications before the interview stage.

The remaining candidates are:

* Montrell Greene, minister at Sycamore Street Church of Christ in Greenwood and founder/executive director of Empowerment 360 Foundation and Montrell Greene Ministries;
* Susan M. Henson, interim superintendent of New Hampshire School Administrative Unit No. 44, Northwood, New Hampshire;
* Arlana Lewin, director of academics and student learning at Madison Parish School Board in Tallulah, Louisiana;
* Karen E. Tutor, retired Mississippi school superintendent and educator from McCall Creek and current independent educational consultant;
* Toyua Watson, director of secondary education for the Concordia Parish School Board.


Greene, Henson, and Lewin will interview on Wednesday, while Tutor and Watson are scheduled for Thursday.  The board may enter executive session, closed to the public and press, during portions of each interview to discuss the candidates' professional competency and character.

Current Superintendent Whest Shirley is working under a month-to-month contract following the board's decision last year not to renew his full contract. Shirley began his superintendency in 2017, preceded by 10 years as an administrator and 22 years as a teacher in Vidalia.
